    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2405120">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2405120">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2405120)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2405120">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2156983&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225333" alt="psul" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2156983)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;" >psul</a></span> <span class="odate time_1447142595 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">10 Nov 2015 08:03</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2405120">
									

<p>For me, those two paragraphs serve three purposes.</p>
<ul>
<li>Most importantly, now that the story is split, the first one provides a little bit of narrative momentum to the re-start of the procedural. By showing that there is human life at risk, the reader is reassured that this isn't merely going to be forensic analysis of gaseous constructs. It's a trick I've stolen from TV, which is appropriate, I think.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Secondly, I agree with sirpudding that (having decided to put them in), I wanted to use them to emphasise that this is the moment at which the story-telling is at its highest point of tension. If this is noir, then the story ends at that point, with no happy ending and no catharsis. If it is another genre, then perhaps June's question will be answered - someone will come.</li>
</ul>
<p>(As an aside on this point, I will take sirpudding's question and raise it: &quot;What did Assistant-Director Griffiths <em>think</em> would happen when he put them on administrative leave?&quot;)</p>
<ul>
<li>Finally, apart from my somewhat heavy-handed literalisation of the title, I also want to reinforce the theme here. The reader's understanding of the story is based on how they interpret the context of the characters' actions, and how they interpret the characters themselves. Is A-D Griffiths simply a heavy-handed bureaucrat, or is he something else? (One interpretation might be that he's actually working with MC&amp;D). Is this the end of the story, or just the end of Act 2? The final question - would no-one come? - is rhetorical in more than just the sense that June's asking it to herself. It is me as author asking it of the audience - what image do you see in this picture?</li>
</ul>

							</div>

								
					
